WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.140
Oh, it's so awesome to see you guys.

00:00:05.140 --> 00:00:08.800
I am loving this conference.

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:13.980
So many amazing people building so many incredible things.

00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:18.380
My background is I've been building browsers since the early 90

00:00:18.380 --> 00:00:19.940
s, if you can believe that.

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:24.620
I've built voice browsers, I've built 3D browsers

00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:29.420
, I've worked on browsers that are really about giving access

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:33.400
and discovery to people who are on an open protocol or on

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:36.080
an open network.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:37.820
This was a browser I worked on.

00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:41.570
I'm very proud to have been one of the team members

00:00:41.570 --> 00:00:44.780
of Netscape Navigator back in the day.

00:00:44.780 --> 00:00:47.140
It was an incredible time.

00:00:47.140 --> 00:00:50.890
At that time, when I joined Netscape, people

00:00:50.890 --> 00:00:55.290
told me I was crazy because AOL was how everyone was

00:00:55.290 --> 00:00:56.750
online.

00:00:56.760 --> 00:00:58.580
AOL was super easy to use.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:01.460
You put a CD-ROM in your computer.

00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:02.460
Crazy.

00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:03.460
But I know.

00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:04.460
But that's what you did.

00:01:04.460 --> 00:01:06.420
And everyone thought that was awesome.

00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:09.060
And when you would talk about the web, they were like

00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:12.000
, hold on a second, I have to download something?

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.000
What does that even mean?

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.740
I have to put in HTTPS?

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:16.930
I'm not doing that.

00:01:16.940 --> 00:01:18.880
That's going nowhere.

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:23.180
And the web really was kind of sort of moving along,

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:25.640
but at a sort of a slow pace.

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:27.960
What happened was two things.

00:01:27.960 --> 00:01:32.870
First of all, people started building amazing websites, completely awesome

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:33.800
websites.

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:38.580
And those websites ultimately started to attract people to the web.

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:42.130
And what Netscape did and what the browser did is

00:01:42.130 --> 00:01:46.270
it acted as a gateway of discovery to find those websites in

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:47.280
the first place.

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:50.950
And then allow you to easily surf those websites across the web

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:51.240
.

00:01:51.240 --> 00:01:55.880
And this was basically the beginning of a virtuous cycle, because

00:01:55.880 --> 00:02:00.200
as more people discovered more websites and could see what it could

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:04.000
do way beyond AOL, they ultimately made more websites and

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:05.160
more people joined.

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:06.740
And this virtuous cycle happened.

00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:10.700
And ultimately, AOL was dethroned as the primary

00:02:10.700 --> 00:02:16.260
walled garden and the main way that we spent time online

00:02:16.410 --> 00:02:16.840
.

00:02:16.840 --> 00:02:20.380
So fast forward to today, we have a new set of

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:21.980
walled gardens.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.250
And these walled gardens are more insidious, because

00:02:25.250 --> 00:02:29.400
they actually own all of our connections to each other.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:30.540
Think about that.

00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:34.500
All of the connections between humans online are owned by just a

00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:35.680
few companies.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:37.460
You guys all know this.

00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:39.960
But this is a huge problem.

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:43.070
And these companies need to be dethroned.

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:44.880
So how do we do that?

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.030
Well, let's get another virtuous cycle going.

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:52.130
There's already some amazing things that are happening on the social

00:02:52.150 --> 00:02:52.640
web.

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:56.000
And when I say the social web, I mean atmosphere,

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:57.140
activity pub.

00:02:57.140 --> 00:03:02.900
These are two open protocols that have allowed us to standardize

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:05.520
human connection online.

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:08.250
That is very, very fundamental.

00:03:08.340 --> 00:03:11.420
And so, of course, what I've been working on

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:14.040
, again, is yet another browser.

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:15.840
This is a new kind of browser.

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:17.980
This is a browser for a new kind of web.

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:20.010
The open social web.

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:21.720
This browser is called Surf.

00:03:21.720 --> 00:03:24.380
It's available as a private beta right now.

00:03:24.380 --> 00:03:26.180
You can actually download it.

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:28.100
Actually, if you go to surf.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:31.400
social, you can sign up for the beta.

00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:34.130
And anyone who signs up today or tomorrow will make sure you

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:34.780
get in.

00:03:34.780 --> 00:03:38.960
So operators are standing by.

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:42.860
And what Surf does is it allows you to not so much

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:46.190
browse websites, but browse feeds.

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:49.560
We think of feeds as the new website, as a new

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:54.430
destination that people can go to on the social web.

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:58.750
Custom feeds are one of the most important things that Blue Sky

00:03:58.750 --> 00:03:59.960
innovated on.

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:02.530
And there's a whole ecosystem of people who have already made

00:04:02.540 --> 00:04:04.820
amazing feeds on things like Graze.

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:07.100
Is Devon here?

00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:11.900
On all sorts of other really fantastic tools.

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:14.900
And what we want to do is help people discover all those

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:15.980
amazing feeds.

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:18.590
And not just, by the way, on @Proto

00:04:18.590 --> 00:04:20.880
, but also on ActivityPub.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:24.750
And there's a whole other dimension of the web, which

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:28.460
is built on RSS, another kind of feed model.

00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:32.610
So what Surf lets you do is it lets you basically browse

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:36.600
and discover and surf any feed on the social web, @

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:39.140
Proto, ActivityPub, RSS, and

00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:44.720
even more interestingly, bring them all together into totally new kinds

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:45.540
of feeds.

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:48.920
So I'll show you a little bit about how you do

00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:49.660
that.

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:53.550
So what you're seeing here is Surf on the desktop web

00:04:53.550 --> 00:04:53.880
.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:55.360
This is actually a preview.

00:04:55.360 --> 00:04:58.090
We're going to be launching this in, knock on wood

00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:02.680
, hopefully a few days later this coming week.

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:05.960
And up at the top you can see you can search all

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:09.220
posts across the social web on ActivityPub, App

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:11.450
Proto, or RSS.

00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:14.420
And they're organized into lots and lots of different feeds.

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:16.500
And then, of course, we can also feature different feeds

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:16.710
.

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:20.610
So we're featuring some fantastically awesome feeds that are on

00:05:20.610 --> 00:05:21.770
the social web.

00:05:21.780 --> 00:05:23.520
Shout out to Rudy with Black Sky.

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:25.650
This is one of the, you know, Black Sky is

00:05:25.650 --> 00:05:27.670
more than just a feed, to be clear.

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:30.320
But people can experience it as a feed.

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:32.360
It's a highly moderated experience.

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:33.740
It's a destination.

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:36.350
It's not just one of many things that you see and

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:39.580
follow in blue sky and shows up in your timeline.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:40.580
It's a destination.

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:41.580
It's a place to go.

00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:42.580
It's highly moderated.

00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:43.580
It's amazing.

00:05:43.580 --> 00:05:45.840
Also, you can see here film feed.

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:47.160
Is David Amell in the audience?

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:48.160
Shout out to David Amell.

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:49.160
He made this.

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:51.890
He's a film photographer.

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:57.100
